</td><td><img src="/images/datel.gif" width=46 height=22 border=0><img src="/images/dateblnk.gif" width=100 height=22 border=0><img src="/images/dater.gif" width=306 height=22 border=0></td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;</td>
	


		<td valign=top width=452><table cellspacing="4" cellpadding="6" width=100% border=0><tr><td background="/images/newsback.gif"><CENTER><H3><FONT FACE="ARIAL" color="#CB723D">Morathi</FONT></H3></CENTER>
			
		<b>Level:</b> Pick One<br>

		<b>Race:</b> Dark Elf<br>

		<b>Class:</b> Necromancer<br>

		<b>PvP Switch:</b>  Off<br>
		
		<center><h4>History:</h4></center>  Morathi’s story begins a simple one. Her family was neither wealthy nor poor.  She was a daughter of two mining-class dark elves.  Due to a possible innate psychological link, she bonded strongly with her twin brother Rakarth. Although Morathi showed signs of above average intelligence, her frail build drowned any chance of being selected into the City Guard.  Rakarth, however, was much more fortunate.  Recruiters saw potential in the young Teir'Dal and placed him into warrior training.  Morathi was jealous of her twin brother, for any mining Dark Elf knew that becoming a City Guard was the only real chance of moving up in the caste-system. Growing up in the crime-filled, labor-class outskirts of Neriak, Morathi was taught basic self-defense from her twin brother when he was allowed to visit the family. Because of her youth and the price of hard metals, her training was constricted to that of small daggers and large wooden staffs.  Being a strong and intelligent Dark Elf, Rakarth was chosen to study the path of a Shadow Knight.  However, Rakarth did have a secret hobby in which he shared with his twin sister.  It was known as the mystic art of Necromancy.  Rakarth’s trainer was an aspiring Necromancer.  When his trainer would leave him unattended, Rakarth would copy sections of Necromancy books onto paper for further studying. Only the most powerful Dark Elf mages were allowed to study this art, so the siblings’ study sessions had to be kept secret.  Morathi’s exceptional intellect coupled with the thrill of studying a forbidden skill made this hobby evolve into an obsession. Because of this, she studied this dark magic diligently.  It was a refreshing break from the hard, monotonous work in the mines. Other than her secret studies, Morathi matured normally. <br>   Many years later, however, Morathi’s life would become far from ordinary.  It has been many years since Morathi lived with her parents.  After evolving into a mature, attractive Dark Elf, Morathi had chosen a spouse.  His name was Eyrlian, and he too was a miner.  Before long the two had a child, Dwyer.  The three of them mined and led content lives for a short while.   However, resources were becoming scarce for the city of Neriak.<br>   It was soon decided that groups of miners were to travel beyond the city limits of Neriak with military escort and harvest the resources of nearby territories in order for the city to thrive.  After several trial excursions, the large excavation would begin.  The trials were a success.  <br>   The excavation consisted of about 50 miners.  More would be sent in a day to retrieve their production.  Morathi, her spouse Eyrlian, her maturing child Dwyer, and her aging parents were among the Dark Elves living in the district that was selected to perform this mission.   And as fate would have it, Rakarth was the captain of the 10 guards sent to protect the caravan.  This was his first mission as captain.<br>   The caravan quickly set off for the neighboring mountains.  As they made their way through a dense mountain forest, a guard spots a destroyed bridge that lies in their path.  “This cannot be.” exclaims Rakarth.  “The scouting reports as of yesterday claim this bridge to be in tact.  Something is not right.”  The next few moments seemed like they lasted hours for Morathi.  Just seconds after her brother’s statement, Morathi hears several loud “whisps”.  A fraction of a second later, she hears several loud moans followed by 4 or 5 collapsing guards.  Even before panic can ensue among the shocked crowd, 3 more guards and 4 miners drop with arrows in their upper torso.  In an obvious state of shock, the frightened Morathi stands like a statue and observes the ensuing chaos.  The unarmed miners scatter in attempt to flee.  They do not get very far.  Large and well armed Humans seem to appear from every angle.  Some appear from behind large rocks, others appear from behind trees and bushes.  Their effects are similar though, with each and every swing of their weapon, a Dark Elf drops.  A group of 8 miners or so rush a weak point in the Human’s attack with their mining axes and shovels.  The courageous and out-armed miners severely wound 2 of their attackers.  The containment has been broken!  Several others see this and make a break for the path down the mountain.  Morathi can see that her parents are in this crowd.  Just then, a frail human in a large robe reveals himself in the path in front of the fleeing crowd of 10 or so.  He was apparently using a cowardly invisibility spell!  As the crowd rushed towards him, the mage became covered in magical lights.  Intimidated by the light show, the crowd slows down.  With a single flick of his wrist, the group becomes engulfed in flames.  The screams of agony almost drown out that of Morathi’s brother.  As she turned towards him, she had just seen the Halfling letting go of the dagger he inserted into my Rakarth’s back.  His erratic convulsions lead her to believe it was an enchanted or poisoned weapon.  All of the guards have appeared to have been defeated.  Wood Elves jump out of the trees replacing their bows with daggers, to help their Human comrades finish the genocide.  Her spouse lies just to the left of her, with 2 arrows in his back.  Her son lies even closer to her on the right, an arrow to the chest and leg.  Her parents lie dead in the mountain path, their bodies still on fire.  Her twin brother’s limp corpse is convulsing on the ground, obviously still having body spasms from the murderous weapon.  Feeling weak, Morathi drops to her hands and knees.  She soon realizes that an arrow in the back and stomach are causing her weakness.  Intense pain then sets in.<br>   Writhing in pain and agony, Morathi looks up and sees a large, bearded human wearing gold platemail dismounting from his horse.  <br>   “T’appears this operation was a great success.” The Human proudly states.<br>   “T’was indeed.”  replies a highly decorated Wood Elf.<br>   “Erollisi Marr will be pleased.” states the Human.<br>   “How can your so-called God of Love approve of the merciless killings of unarmed people?!” shouts Morathi in a scratchy voice.  <br>   “People?” asks the Human.  “You Dark Elves are not people.  You are daemons put on this world to bring us pain and hardships.  I have no mercy for daemons.”<br>   “The only monsters present here today are you and your murderers!” Morathi whispers.<br>   “Silence!  I grow tired of our conversation.  You look to be in a lot of pain Dark Elf.  To show you how compassionate Erollisi Marr is, I shall give you 5 minutes to suffer, or pray to your false God to end your suffering.  The decision is yours.  Once those 5 minutes are up, if you are still alive, I will end your suffering myself.  You need not thank me for this opportunity.  T’is a paladin’s job.” says the human with an ironically evil grin as he tuns and walks away.<br>   The pain in Morathi’s body quickly shifts from anger to hate.  While on the ground, she begins to mumble words and sounds indistinguishable to her Human and Wood Elven attackers.  <br>   “Listen lads, the daemon is praying to Innoruuk for help.  Should we flee to avoid his wrath?”  the paladin says laughing.  Everyone else joins in on the laughter.<br>   What the Wood Elves and Humans do not know is that Morathi is not praying to her God of Hate.  Instead, she is channeling the Necromanic spell of “Animate Dead”, one of the most complex spells she has ever studied over the last 50 years.  <br>   The chuckles soon fade as mystical lights cover the bloody forest clearing.  <br>   “Mage, what is that magical act being conjured?” asks the paladin.<br>   “I-I do not know sir.  I have never seen anything quite like it.” replies the mage.<br>   As the light subsides, the paladin states “Not to worry lads, it appears to be going away.”<br>   Just as the paladin finishes speaking, he feels a firm hand grasp his ankle.  It is the hand of a Dark Elf that was nearly severed at the waist!  Another man screams in terror as the flaming bodies in the road rise to their feet.  Slain guards and miners alike slowly rise with weapons in hand.  The soulless stare of the dead send chills down the living’s spines.<br>   “T’is the wrath of Innoruuk!  We must flee!  Flee for your lives!” yells the paladin, kicking the hand off of his ankle.  The band of warriors flee just as quickly as they attacked.<br>   As soon as the last warrior was out of sight, every one of the bodies dropped back into their lifeless slumber.  Even more exhausted than before, Morathi collapses.  To study Necromancy was one thing, the actual performance was another.  Realizing that her wounds were far too serious to ignore for even a minute more, Morathi crawled to the sound of a man suffering.  It was one of the fallen Humans.  It appears they were mending his severe wounds before they fled.  <br>   “For once I am glad to see you, Human.”  she whispers to the dying man.  She closes her eyes and remembers a significantly easier spell translated as “Life Drain”.  Morathi begins to feel her wounds heal as she drains the last breath from the human’s life force.<br>This magical bandage is enough for her to make it back to the city.  Once there, she notifies the local magistrate about the attack and reports to a healer. When asked how she escaped, she simply replies that she was “Blessed by Innoruuk.”  She is endowed with all of her family’s worldly possessions, including her brother’s Necromancy studies.  Bitter and vengeful, she has given up her position as a miner and vowed to study this dark art until perfection or death, whichever comes first. <br>   <br>   <br>   <br>   <br>   <br>
